You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. You\ncan also load graph data that\'s stored in Amazon S3.\n\nYou can get started by [creating a new Neptune Analytics graph](./create-\ngraph-using-console.html) and loading data into it in a number of ways.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/what-is-neptune-analytics.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '2cc987d36f15b03b01c4d1db95ff660b']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics is a memory-optimized graph database engine for analytics.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='037860cc-5f8a-40a9-8cee-7ea1cf9d5348', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '9d0ffde6e4db0eabd27a2190db38c5cb', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics uses popular graph analytic algorithms.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:f510e9a6', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nvs-neptune-database "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# When to use Neptune Analytics and when to use Neptune Database\n\nAmazon Neptune makes it easy to work with graph data in the AWS Cloud. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '47f1d631fb3dbc0e7b3cb0e5296b759a']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics provides a simple API for loading graph data.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='2a4a87d6-6df2-4e72-a590-5c4732369a84', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': 'f1d73f6c5a6b26d40ed51768ace0b155', 'value': 'Users can load data from a Neptune Database snapshot into Neptune Analytics for intensive analysis.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115:24d5bb50', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#what-is-neptune-\nanalytics "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# What is Neptune Analytics?\n\nNeptune Analytics is a memory-optimized graph database engine for analytics.\nWith Neptune Analytics, you can get insights and find trends by processing\nlarge amounts of graph data in seconds. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. '[](/pdfs/neptune/latest/userguide/neptune-ug.pdf#intro "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune](/neptune/index.html)[User\nGuide](intro.html)\n\n# What Is Amazon Neptune?\n\nAmazon Neptune is a fast, reliable, fully managed graph database service that\nmakes it easy to build and run applications that work with highly connected\ndatasets. The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 3, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '406b28c77fcb166704fe59dd8c50904c', '7d5f46e9147cc18ff490459a16a84c14']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Amazon Neptune offers continuous backup to Amazon S3.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='c2d316df-b797-4f45-b94c-bc0c4d860309', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '502be7dc1186944d5d5e5e068fda9900', 'value': 'Neptune enables creation of sophisticated, interactive graph applications.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. Security\nfeatures include network isolation using [Amazon\nVPC](https://aws.amazon.com/vpc/), and encryption at rest using keys that you\ncreate and control through [AWS Key Management Service (AWS\nKMS)](https://aws.amazon.com/kms/). On an encrypted Neptune instance, data in\nthe underlying storage is encrypted, as are the automated backups, snapshots,\nand replicas in the same cluster.\n\n###### Fully Managed\n\nWith Amazon Neptune, you donâ\x80\x99t have to worry about database management tasks\nlike hardware provisioning, software patching, setup, configuration, or\nbackups.\n\nYou can use Neptune to create sophisticated, interactive graph applications\nthat can query billions of relationships in milliseconds. SQL queries for\nhighly connected data are complex and hard to tune for performance. With\nNeptune, you can use the popular graph query languages Gremlin, openCypher,\nand SPARQL to execute powerful queries that are easy to write and perform well\non connected data. This capability significantly reduces code complexity so\nthat you can quickly create applications that process relationships.\n\nNeptune is designed to offer greater than 99.99 percent availability. Each Neptune DB cluster has one primary DB instance that is responsible for writing (that is, loading or modifying) graph database contents.\n\n  * _Neptune replica_ â\x80\x93 Connects to the same storage volume as the primary DB instance and supports only read operations. Each Neptune DB cluster can have up to 15 Neptune Replicas in addition to the primary DB instance. This provides high availability by locating Neptune Replicas in separate Availability Zones and distribution load from reading clients.\n\n  * _Cluster volume_ â\x80\x93 Neptune data is stored in the cluster volume, which is designed for reliability and high availability. A cluster volume consists of copies of the data across multiple Availability Zones in a single AWS Region. Because your data is automatically replicated across Availability Zones, it is highly durable, and there is little possibility of data loss.\n\n###### Supports Open Graph APIs\n\nAmazon Neptune supports open graph APIs for both property graphs (Gremlin and\nopenCypher) and RDF graphs (SPARQL). It provides high performance for both of\nthese graph models and their query languages. You can choose the Property\nGraph (PG) model and access the same graph with both the [openCypher query\nlanguage](./access-graph-opencypher.html) and/or the [Gremlin query\nlanguage](./access-graph-gremlin.html).'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 4, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '406b28c77fcb166704fe59dd8c50904c', '7d5f46e9147cc18ff490459a16a84c14', 'fd9ea1f73b7bd4c9a327a22889bb072a']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Amazon Neptune has Neptune replicas.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='2901acf4-a13a-4a8c-899d-71e8efd94c56', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '3530a9e7c36e08b57bd4a8685e8c9a8d', 'value': 'Neptune provides multiple levels of security for databases.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. Security\nfeatures include network isolation using [Amazon\nVPC](https://aws.amazon.com/vpc/), and encryption at rest using keys that you\ncreate and control through [AWS Key Management Service (AWS\nKMS)](https://aws.amazon.com/kms/). SQL queries for\nhighly connected data are complex and hard to tune for performance. With\nNeptune, you can use the popular graph query languages Gremlin, openCypher,\nand SPARQL to execute powerful queries that are easy to write and perform well\non connected data. The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. You\ncan also load graph data that\'s stored in Amazon S3.\n\nYou can get started by [creating a new Neptune Analytics graph](./create-\ngraph-using-console.html) and loading data into it in a number of ways.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '9d0ffde6e4db0eabd27a2190db38c5cb', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics uses popular graph analytic algorithms.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:f510e9a6', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nvs-neptune-database "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# When to use Neptune Analytics and when to use Neptune Database\n\nAmazon Neptune makes it easy to work with graph data in the AWS Cloud. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': 'e612590362e3a8c95bb72d180cb07eb2', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics uses popular graph analytic algorithms.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:70ee99d9', 'value': "Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.\n\n[Neptune Analytics](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-\nanalytics/latest/userguide/what-is-neptune-analytics.html) is an analytics\ndatabase engine that complements Neptune database and that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '71b713c91ff78a6df94b8dbd88370700', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics allows running custom graph analytics queries.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-features.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412:60a838ca', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nfeatures "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# Neptune Analytics Features\n\nNeptune Analytics operates in a managed environment that can load data\nextremely fast into memory and run graph algorithms natively. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. You can then run graph analytics queries using pre-\nbuilt or custom graph queries.\n\n![Warning](https://d1ge0kk1l5kms0.cloudfront.net/images/G/01/webservices/console/warning.png)\n**Javascript is disabled or is unavailable in your browser.**\n\nTo use the Amazon Web Services Documentation, Javascript must be enabled.\nPlease refer to your browser\'s Help pages for instructions.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '13bd43ec2b0ca32e2453f475851fedf7', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics provides a simple API for analyzing graph data.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:f510e9a6', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nvs-neptune-database "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# When to use Neptune Analytics and when to use Neptune Database\n\nAmazon Neptune makes it easy to work with graph data in the AWS Cloud. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. You\ncan also load graph data that\'s stored in Amazon S3.\n\nYou can get started by [creating a new Neptune Analytics graph](./create-\ngraph-using-console.html) and loading data into it in a number of ways.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': 'c62e745422b4e50159795ce39612cd87', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics is a concept mentioned in the Amazon Web Services Documentation.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-features.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412:8c0683c2', 'value': "**\n\nTo use the Amazon Web Services Documentation, Javascript must be enabled.\nPlease refer to your browser's Help pages for instructions.\n\n[Document Conventions](/general/latest/gr/docconventions.html)\n\nWhat is Neptune Analytics?\n\nNeptune Analytics vs. Neptune Database\n\nDid this page help you? - Yes\n\nThanks for letting us know we're doing a good job!\n\nIf you've got a moment, please tell us what we did right so we can do more of\nit.\n\nDid this page help you? - No\n\nThanks for letting us know this page needs work. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. You can then run graph analytics queries using pre-\nbuilt or custom graph queries.\n\n![Warning](https://d1ge0kk1l5kms0.cloudfront.net/images/G/01/webservices/console/warning.png)\n**Javascript is disabled or is unavailable in your browser.**\n\nTo use the Amazon Web Services Documentation, Javascript must be enabled.\nPlease refer to your browser\'s Help pages for instructions.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '7439d5b3ee8178a1b56fbbb456edd79d', 'value': 'Neptune Database is a serverless graph database.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:f510e9a6', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nvs-neptune-database "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# When to use Neptune Analytics and when to use Neptune Database\n\nAmazon Neptune makes it easy to work with graph data in the AWS Cloud. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '46ed7d55f8218409b65c62288d0bbdc1', 'value': 'Users can load data from a Neptune Database graph into Neptune Analytics for intensive analysis.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/what-is-neptune-analytics.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115:24d5bb50', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#what-is-neptune-\nanalytics "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# What is Neptune Analytics?\n\nNeptune Analytics is a memory-optimized graph database engine for analytics.\nWith Neptune Analytics, you can get insights and find trends by processing\nlarge amounts of graph data in seconds. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. You\ncan also load graph data that\'s stored in Amazon S3.\n\nYou can get started by [creating a new Neptune Analytics graph](./create-\ngraph-using-console.html) and loading data into it in a number of ways.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '08f88736b3c4ee1966b3ed855658288a', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics offers graph as a service.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-features.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412:60a838ca', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nfeatures "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# Neptune Analytics Features\n\nNeptune Analytics operates in a managed environment that can load data\nextremely fast into memory and run graph algorithms natively. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': 'd3ab7f4d0f6a6a14ef7e842f70bb19a7', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics provisions compute resources based on graph size.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-features.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412:60a838ca', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nfeatures "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# Neptune Analytics Features\n\nNeptune Analytics operates in a managed environment that can load data\nextremely fast into memory and run graph algorithms natively. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. You\ncan also load graph data that\'s stored in Amazon S3.\n\nYou can get started by [creating a new Neptune Analytics graph](./create-\ngraph-using-console.html) and loading data into it in a number of ways.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '2991cd9eac821bf8a60d83e54068bead', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics manages graphs instead of infrastructure.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-features.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412:60a838ca', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nfeatures "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# Neptune Analytics Features\n\nNeptune Analytics operates in a managed environment that can load data\nextremely fast into memory and run graph algorithms natively. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. You can then run graph analytics queries using pre-\nbuilt or custom graph queries.\n\n![Warning](https://d1ge0kk1l5kms0.cloudfront.net/images/G/01/webservices/console/warning.png)\n**Javascript is disabled or is unavailable in your browser.**\n\nTo use the Amazon Web Services Documentation, Javascript must be enabled.\nPlease refer to your browser\'s Help pages for instructions.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '66bc799faf4b0bbf907f3c4386a6a3e8', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics supports a library of optimized graph analytic algorithms.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/what-is-neptune-analytics.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115:24d5bb50', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#what-is-neptune-\nanalytics "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# What is Neptune Analytics?\n\nNeptune Analytics is a memory-optimized graph database engine for analytics.\nWith Neptune Analytics, you can get insights and find trends by processing\nlarge amounts of graph data in seconds. The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '502be7dc1186944d5d5e5e068fda9900', 'value': 'Neptune enables creation of sophisticated, interactive graph applications.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. Security\nfeatures include network isolation using [Amazon\nVPC](https://aws.amazon.com/vpc/), and encryption at rest using keys that you\ncreate and control through [AWS Key Management Service (AWS\nKMS)](https://aws.amazon.com/kms/). On an encrypted Neptune instance, data in\nthe underlying storage is encrypted, as are the automated backups, snapshots,\nand replicas in the same cluster.\n\n###### Fully Managed\n\nWith Amazon Neptune, you donâ\x80\x99t have to worry about database management tasks\nlike hardware provisioning, software patching, setup, configuration, or\nbackups.\n\nYou can use Neptune to create sophisticated, interactive graph applications\nthat can query billions of relationships in milliseconds. SQL queries for\nhighly connected data are complex and hard to tune for performance. With\nNeptune, you can use the popular graph query languages Gremlin, openCypher,\nand SPARQL to execute powerful queries that are easy to write and perform well\non connected data. This capability significantly reduces code complexity so\nthat you can quickly create applications that process relationships.\n\nNeptune is designed to offer greater than 99.99 percent availability. It\nincreases database performance and availability by tightly integrating the\ndatabase engine with an SSD-backed virtualized storage layer that is built for\ndatabase workloads.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '19c97c3414a2786d400a51849507d5e9', 'value': "Neptune's virtualized storage layer is built for database workloads.", 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. It\nincreases database performance and availability by tightly integrating the\ndatabase engine with an SSD-backed virtualized storage layer that is built for\ndatabase workloads.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': 'fd9ea1f73b7bd4c9a327a22889bb072a', 'value': 'Amazon Neptune has Neptune replicas.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:4200f7a5', 'value': '###### Key Service Components\n\n  * _Primary DB instance_ â\x80\x93 Supports read and write operations, and performs all of the data modifications to the cluster volume. Each Neptune DB cluster has one primary DB instance that is responsible for writing (that is, loading or modifying) graph database contents.\n\n  * _Neptune replica_ â\x80\x93 Connects to the same storage volume as the primary DB instance and supports only read operations. Each Neptune DB cluster can have up to 15 Neptune Replicas in addition to the primary DB instance. This provides high availability by locating Neptune Replicas in separate Availability Zones and distribution load from reading clients.\n\n  * _Cluster volume_ â\x80\x93 Neptune data is stored in the cluster volume, which is designed for reliability and high availability. A cluster volume consists of copies of the data across multiple Availability Zones in a single AWS Region. Because your data is automatically replicated across Availability Zones, it is highly durable, and there is little possibility of data loss.\n\n###### Supports Open Graph APIs\n\nAmazon Neptune supports open graph APIs for both property graphs (Gremlin and\nopenCypher) and RDF graphs (SPARQL). It provides high performance for both of\nthese graph models and their query languages. You can choose the Property\nGraph (PG) model and access the same graph with both the [openCypher query\nlanguage](./access-graph-opencypher.html) and/or the [Gremlin query\nlanguage](./access-graph-gremlin.html).'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '3530a9e7c36e08b57bd4a8685e8c9a8d', 'value': 'Neptune provides multiple levels of security for databases.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. It\nincreases database performance and availability by tightly integrating the\ndatabase engine with an SSD-backed virtualized storage layer that is built for\ndatabase workloads.'}}}, {'result': {'statement': {'statementId': '12985132fd62b0cae98b7489d195c14b', 'value': 'Amazon Neptune is a graph database service.', 'details': ''}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:84e4f5ad', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune/latest/userguide/neptune-ug.pdf#intro "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune](/neptune/index.html)[User\nGuide](intro.html)\n\n# What Is Amazon Neptune?\n\nAmazon Neptune is a fast, reliable, fully managed graph database service that\nmakes it easy to build and run applications that work with highly connected\ndatasets. The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.'}}}]

It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. You\ncan also load graph data that\'s stored in Amazon S3.\n\nYou can get started by [creating a new Neptune Analytics graph](./create-\ngraph-using-console.html) and loading data into it in a number of ways.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/what-is-neptune-analytics.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '2cc987d36f15b03b01c4d1db95ff660b']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics is a memory-optimized graph database engine for analytics.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='b34fb8e2-3680-4229-b277-891c86498183', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '9d0ffde6e4db0eabd27a2190db38c5cb', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics uses popular graph analytic algorithms.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:f510e9a6', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nvs-neptune-database "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# When to use Neptune Analytics and when to use Neptune Database\n\nAmazon Neptune makes it easy to work with graph data in the AWS Cloud. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '9d0ffde6e4db0eabd27a2190db38c5cb']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics uses popular graph analytic algorithms.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='2856818c-b199-4efb-984a-81b0f1b1029d', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': 'e612590362e3a8c95bb72d180cb07eb2', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics uses popular graph analytic algorithms.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:70ee99d9', 'value': "Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.\n\n[Neptune Analytics](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-\nanalytics/latest/userguide/what-is-neptune-analytics.html) is an analytics\ndatabase engine that complements Neptune database and that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', 'b5cbe02dfa30e30073c8b0971b61cc69']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics provides a simple API for querying graph data.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='17256a45-4045-4d4a-b469-43464c685bdf', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '71b713c91ff78a6df94b8dbd88370700', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics allows running custom graph analytics queries.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412:60a838ca', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nfeatures "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# Neptune Analytics Features\n\nNeptune Analytics operates in a managed environment that can load data\nextremely fast into memory and run graph algorithms natively. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. You can then run graph analytics queries using pre-\nbuilt or custom graph queries.\n\n![Warning](https://d1ge0kk1l5kms0.cloudfront.net/images/G/01/webservices/console/warning.png)\n**Javascript is disabled or is unavailable in your browser.**\n\nTo use the Amazon Web Services Documentation, Javascript must be enabled.\nPlease refer to your browser\'s Help pages for instructions.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:4510583f:e412', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-features.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '71b713c91ff78a6df94b8dbd88370700']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics allows running custom graph analytics queries.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='3b2fa30f-a2db-41f2-b13c-dfcc81815195', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '13bd43ec2b0ca32e2453f475851fedf7', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics provides a simple API for analyzing graph data.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:f510e9a6', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#neptune-analytics-\nvs-neptune-database "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# When to use Neptune Analytics and when to use Neptune Database\n\nAmazon Neptune makes it easy to work with graph data in the AWS Cloud. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '47f1d631fb3dbc0e7b3cb0e5296b759a']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics provides a simple API for loading graph data.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='95356d37-fd3a-4871-8987-3343f3b65a07', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': 'f1d73f6c5a6b26d40ed51768ace0b155', 'value': 'Users can load data from a Neptune Database snapshot into Neptune Analytics for intensive analysis.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bd6a6b1b:8115:24d5bb50', 'value': '[](/pdfs/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/graph-guide.pdf#what-is-neptune-\nanalytics "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune Analytics](/neptune/index.html)[Neptune\nAnalytics User Guide](what-is-neptune-analytics.html)\n\n# What is Neptune Analytics?\n\nNeptune Analytics is a memory-optimized graph database engine for analytics.\nWith Neptune Analytics, you can get insights and find trends by processing\nlarge amounts of graph data in seconds. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. Amazon\nNeptune includes both Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics.\n\n[Neptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html) is\na serverless graph database designed for optimal scalability and availability.\nIt provides a solution for graph database workloads that need to scale to\n100,000 queries per second, Multi-AZ high availability, and multi-Region\ndeployments. You can use Neptune Database for social networking, fraud\nalerting, and Customer 360 applications.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an analytics database engine that can quickly analyze\nlarge amounts of graph data in memory to get insights and find trends. Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. '[](/pdfs/neptune/latest/userguide/neptune-ug.pdf#intro "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune](/neptune/index.html)[User\nGuide](intro.html)\n\n# What Is Amazon Neptune?\n\nAmazon Neptune is a fast, reliable, fully managed graph database service that\nmakes it easy to build and run applications that work with highly connected\ndatasets. The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 3, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '406b28c77fcb166704fe59dd8c50904c', '7d5f46e9147cc18ff490459a16a84c14']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Amazon Neptune offers continuous backup to Amazon S3.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='139f8871-262b-40dc-af37-ca005d6f54a5', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '502be7dc1186944d5d5e5e068fda9900', 'value': 'Neptune enables creation of sophisticated, interactive graph applications.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. Security\nfeatures include network isolation using [Amazon\nVPC](https://aws.amazon.com/vpc/), and encryption at rest using keys that you\ncreate and control through [AWS Key Management Service (AWS\nKMS)](https://aws.amazon.com/kms/). On an encrypted Neptune instance, data in\nthe underlying storage is encrypted, as are the automated backups, snapshots,\nand replicas in the same cluster.\n\n###### Fully Managed\n\nWith Amazon Neptune, you donâ\x80\x99t have to worry about database management tasks\nlike hardware provisioning, software patching, setup, configuration, or\nbackups.\n\nYou can use Neptune to create sophisticated, interactive graph applications\nthat can query billions of relationships in milliseconds. SQL queries for\nhighly connected data are complex and hard to tune for performance. With\nNeptune, you can use the popular graph query languages Gremlin, openCypher,\nand SPARQL to execute powerful queries that are easy to write and perform well\non connected data. Each Neptune DB cluster has one primary DB instance that is responsible for writing (that is, loading or modifying) graph database contents.\n\n  * _Neptune replica_ â\x80\x93 Connects to the same storage volume as the primary DB instance and supports only read operations. Each Neptune DB cluster can have up to 15 Neptune Replicas in addition to the primary DB instance. This provides high availability by locating Neptune Replicas in separate Availability Zones and distribution load from reading clients.\n\n  * _Cluster volume_ â\x80\x93 Neptune data is stored in the cluster volume, which is designed for reliability and high availability. A cluster volume consists of copies of the data across multiple Availability Zones in a single AWS Region. Because your data is automatically replicated across Availability Zones, it is highly durable, and there is little possibility of data loss.\n\n###### Supports Open Graph APIs\n\nAmazon Neptune supports open graph APIs for both property graphs (Gremlin and\nopenCypher) and RDF graphs (SPARQL). It provides high performance for both of\nthese graph models and their query languages. You can choose the Property\nGraph (PG) model and access the same graph with both the [openCypher query\nlanguage](./access-graph-opencypher.html) and/or the [Gremlin query\nlanguage](./access-graph-gremlin.html).'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 4, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '406b28c77fcb166704fe59dd8c50904c', '7d5f46e9147cc18ff490459a16a84c14', 'fd9ea1f73b7bd4c9a327a22889bb072a']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Amazon Neptune has Neptune replicas.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='13395444-a965-4552-93e1-4e1821efaff6', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '3530a9e7c36e08b57bd4a8685e8c9a8d', 'value': 'Neptune provides multiple levels of security for databases.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b:fa413ccd', 'value': 'If you use the W3C standard Resource\nDescription Framework (RDF) model, you can access your graph using the\nstandard [SPARQL query language](./access-graph-sparql.html).\n\n###### Highly Secure\n\nNeptune provides multiple levels of security for your database. Security\nfeatures include network isolation using [Amazon\nVPC](https://aws.amazon.com/vpc/), and encryption at rest using keys that you\ncreate and control through [AWS Key Management Service (AWS\nKMS)](https://aws.amazon.com/kms/). SQL queries for\nhighly connected data are complex and hard to tune for performance. With\nNeptune, you can use the popular graph query languages Gremlin, openCypher,\nand SPARQL to execute powerful queries that are easy to write and perform well\non connected data.
