The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. Neptune is fully managed, so you no longer need to worry\nabout database management tasks like hardware provisioning, software patching,\nsetup, configuration, or backups.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:abd5427c:978b', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 4, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '406b28c77fcb166704fe59dd8c50904c', '7d5f46e9147cc18ff490459a16a84c14', '12985132fd62b0cae98b7489d195c14b']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Amazon Neptune is a graph database service.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0)]

Neptune\nAnalytics is a solution for quickly analyzing existing graph databases or\ngraph datasets stored in a data lake. It uses popular graph analytic\nalgorithms and low-latency analytic queries.\n\nYou can use Neptune Analytics to analyze and query graphs in data science\nworkflows that build targeted content recommendations, assist with fraud\ninvestigations, and detect network threats.\n\nBy providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.'}, 'source': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'metadata': {'sourceId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc', 'url': 'https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune-analytics/latest/userguide/neptune-analytics-vs-neptune-database.html'}}, 'search_type': 'beam_search', 'depth': 2, 'path': ['04e12b80ae9e55bba2f03d41677f2a5d', '47f1d631fb3dbc0e7b3cb0e5296b759a']}, excluded_embed_metadata_keys=[], excluded_llm_metadata_keys=[], relationships={}, metadata_template='{key}: {value}', metadata_separator='\n', text='Neptune Analytics provides a simple API for loading graph data.', mimetype='text/plain', start_char_idx=None, end_char_idx=None, metadata_seperator='\n', text_template='{metadata_str}\n\n{content}'), score=0.0), NodeWithScore(node=TextNode(id_='86fe5192-8b50-433b-ad06-3c2215368dc9', embedding=None, metadata={'statement': {'statementId': '0e4c8a88fbe65688193e65cb0b274689', 'value': 'Neptune Analytics can process thousands of analytic queries per second.', 'details': ''}, 'chunk': {'chunkId': 'aws:awsgraph1:bf585e13:3edc:5dffdd3a', 'value': "By providing a simple API for loading, querying, and analyzing graph data,\nNeptune Analytics also removes the overhead of building and managing complex\ndata-analytics pipelines.\n\nNeptune Analytics makes it easy to apply powerful algorithms both to the data\nin your Neptune Database and to graph data that's stored externally. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. To analyze graph data quickly and\neasily, Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory. It supports a\nlibrary of optimized graph analytic algorithms, low-latency graph queries, and\nvector search capabilities within graph traversals.\n\nNeptune Analytics is an ideal choice for investigatory, exploratory, or data-\nscience workloads that require fast iteration for data, analytical and\nalgorithmic processing, or vector search on graph data. It complements [Amazon\nNeptune\nDatabase](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/intro.html), a\npopular managed graph database. To perform intensive analysis, you can load\nthe data from a Neptune Database graph or snapshot into Neptune Analytics. With Neptune\nAnalytics, you can perform in-database analytics on large graphs.\n\nThis functionality lets you perform business intelligence and custom\nanalytical queries, and use pre-built graph algorithms with the openCypher\nlanguage. For example, with Neptune Analytics you can ingest text from\ncybersecurity reports to analyze relationships within security environments\nand calculate vulnerability mitigations using graph algorithms or openCypher\nqueries.\n\nNeptune Analytics offers a graph as a service experience by managing graphs\ninstead of infrastructure, so you can focus on queries and workflows to solve\nproblems. It automatically provisions the compute resources necessary to run\nanalytics workloads based on the size of the graph.\n\nYou can load graph data into Neptune Analytics from Amazon S3 or from a\nNeptune Database endpoint. '[](/pdfs/neptune/latest/userguide/neptune-ug.pdf#intro "Open PDF")\n\n[Documentation](/index.html)[Neptune](/neptune/index.html)[User\nGuide](intro.html)\n\n# What Is Amazon Neptune?\n\nAmazon Neptune is a fast, reliable, fully managed graph database service that\nmakes it easy to build and run applications that work with highly connected\ndatasets. The core of Neptune is a purpose-built, high-performance graph\ndatabase engine. This engine is optimized for storing billions of\nrelationships and querying the graph with milliseconds latency. Neptune\nsupports the popular property-graph query languages Apache TinkerPop Gremlin\nand Neo4j\'s openCypher, and the W3C\'s RDF query language, SPARQL. This enables\nyou to build queries that efficiently navigate highly connected datasets.\nNeptune powers graph use cases such as recommendation engines, fraud\ndetection, knowledge graphs, drug discovery, and network security.\n\nThe Neptune database is highly available, with read replicas, point-in-time\nrecovery, continuous backup to Amazon S3, and replication across Availability\nZones. Neptune provides data security features, with support for encryption at\nrest and in transit. Neptune Database and Neptune Analytics are distinct components of Amazon Neptune with several key differences:

1. Purpose: Neptune Database is a fully managed graph database service, while Neptune Analytics is an analytics database engine designed for getting insights and finding trends in graph data [source_1, source_2].

2. Use cases: Neptune Database is suitable for applications like fraud alerting, Customer 360, and social networking [source_1]. Neptune Analytics is ideal for data science workloads, investigatory and exploratory tasks, and workloads requiring fast iteration for analytical, data, and algorithmic processing [source_2].

3. Data processing: Neptune Database is designed for optimal scalability and availability, handling up to 100,000 queries per second [source_1]. Neptune Analytics can process thousands of analytic queries per second and quickly analyze large amounts of graph data in memory [source_1, source_2].

4. Features: Neptune Database offers multi-Region deployments and Multi-AZ high availability [source_1]. Neptune Analytics provides a library of optimized graph analytic algorithms, vector search capabilities within graph traversals, and supports low-latency graph queries [source_2].

5. Data storage: Neptune Analytics stores large graph datasets in memory for fast processing [source_2], while Neptune Database uses a virtualized storage layer built for database workloads [source_4].

6. Data loading: Neptune Analytics can load data from Neptune Database snapshots, graphs stored in Amazon S3, or directly from a Neptune Database endpoint [source_2, source_3].

7. Query language: Neptune Analytics uses the openCypher language for querying and analyzing graph data [source_3].

8. Resource management: Neptune Analytics automatically provisions compute resources based on graph size for analytics workloads [source_3].

In summary, Neptune Database is optimized for operational graph database workloads, while Neptune Analytics is designed for intensive graph analysis, data science, and deriving insights from large graph datasets [source_1, source_2].
